# Main/Gesture.elm — EARLY

The pointer-gesture layer of the Elm client. Owns every
function that sits between a physical mousedown and the
WireAction it eventually produces, plus the per-hand-card
styling hook that renders the drag-affordance feedback.

## Status

- **Label:** EARLY. Extracted 2026-04-19 from the pre-split
  `Main.elm` monolith. Cohesive unit — all the drag machinery
  plus the helpers a view needs to wire mousedowns.

## Public API

- `startBoardCardDrag : {stackIndex, cardIndex} -> Point ->
  Model -> (Model, Cmd Msg)` — begins a drag from a board
  card. Computes wings via `WingOracle.wingsForStack`, sets
  `clickIntent = Just cardIndex` (so an unmoved release
  becomes a Split), fires `fetchBoardRect`.
- `startHandDrag : Int -> Point -> Model -> (Model, Cmd Msg)`
  — begins a drag from a hand card. Wings via
  `WingOracle.wingsForHandCard`, `clickIntent = Nothing`
  (hand cards have no split semantic).
- `fetchBoardRect : Cmd Msg` — `Browser.Dom.getElement
  boardDomId` → `Task.attempt BoardRectReceived`.
- `handleMouseUp : Model -> (Model, Cmd Msg)` — resolves
  gesture → clears drag → applies WireAction via
  `Apply.applyAction |> Apply.commit` (outcome's status
  becomes the new status bar text) → decides what gesture
  (if any) to ship via `gestureForAction` → appends to
  actionLog → fires `sendAction`. For rejected gestures, may
  instead write the off-board scold status via
  `droppedOffBoardScold`.
- `clearDrag : Model -> Model` — `{ model | drag =
  NotDragging }`.
- `pointDecoder : Decoder Point` — `{clientX, clientY}` →
  Point.
- `cardMouseDown : Int -> Int -> List (Html.Attribute Msg)`
  — mousedown handler for a board card; emits
  `MouseDownOnBoardCard`.
- `handCardAttrs : DragState -> List Card -> Int -> HandCard
  -> List (Html.Attribute Msg)` — per-hand-card attribute
  list: hint-green background + mousedown handler + drag-dim
  opacity.

## Gesture resolution (the central branch table)

`resolveGesture` (not exported — internal helper for
`handleMouseUp`) dispatches on `(clickIntent, source,
hoveredWing, cursorOverBoard)`:

| clickIntent | source | hoveredWing | overBoard | Result |
|---|---|---|---|---|
| Just cardIdx | FromBoardStack idx | — | — | `Split { stackIndex, cardIndex }` |
| Nothing | FromBoardStack idx | Just wing | — | `MergeStack { source=idx, target=wing.stackIndex, side }` |
| Nothing | FromHandCard idx | Just wing | — | `MergeHand { handCard, target=wing.stackIndex, side }` |
| Nothing | FromHandCard idx | Nothing | True + loc | `PlaceHand { handCard, loc }` |
| Nothing | FromBoardStack idx | Nothing | True + loc | `MoveStack { stackIndex, newLoc=loc }` |
| any | any | any | drop before rect arrives | `Nothing` (gesture discarded) |

## Click-vs-drag arbitration

`clickIntent` starts as `Just cardIndex` for board-card drags
(hand drags get `Nothing`). Each MouseMove feeds
`GestureArbitration.clickIntentAfterMove` which kills the
intent (flips to `Nothing`) once the cursor moves beyond a
threshold. The call site for that is currently in
`Main.elm`'s `MouseMove` handler (not in this module) because
it's a one-liner that needs `info` unpacking anyway.

## Gesture shipping rule (2026-04-22)

`gestureForAction` decides what rides alongside the WireAction:

- **Hand-origin actions** (`MergeHand`, `PlaceHand`) — always
  `Nothing`. Elm's replay resolves hand origins via live DOM
  measurement regardless of sender; a captured viewport-frame
  path would be stale after any window resize and is never
  consulted at replay time. Matches Python.
- **Intra-board actions** (`Split`, `MergeStack`, `MoveStack`)
  — `Just { path, frame = BoardFrame }`. Viewport-captured
  samples get the live board rect's `(x, y)` subtracted at
  send time, producing env-durable board-frame coords. The
  board's internal geometry is fixed (800×600); only its
  viewport position can drift, and rect subtraction absorbs
  that drift exactly.
- **Fallback** — if `info.boardRect` never arrived (a
  `fetchBoardRect` race that effectively doesn't happen in
  practice), ship the untranslated path tagged as
  `ViewportFrame`. Server accepts; replay reads the frame tag
  and still renders correctly in the matching env.
- **Other actions** (`CompleteTurn`, `Undo`) — `Nothing`.

The invariant this preserves: **every intra-board action on
the wire carries a path that's faithful to replay forever,
regardless of future viewport or DPR changes.** Matches the
architecture doc's "durable always" rule.

## Drop-loc derivation

`dropLoc info = info.boardRect |> Maybe.map (rect ->
{left = cursor.x - grabOffset.x - rect.x, top = cursor.y -
grabOffset.y - rect.y})`. Returns `Nothing` if the board rect
hasn't arrived yet — the race between drag-start and
`Browser.Dom.getElement` completing is benign but callers
must handle `Nothing`.

## handCardAttrs branches

1. **Hint highlight** — if `hc.card` is in `hintedCards`, add
   `background-color: lightgreen`.
2. **Not dragging** — attach `MouseDownOnHandCard idx`.
3. **Dragging, this is the source card** — `opacity: 0.35;
   pointer-events: none` (dim the source, let the floater
   show).
4. **Dragging, any other card (hand or board source)** —
   `pointer-events: none` (disable interaction during drag).

## What this module deliberately does NOT do

- **Subscriptions.** `Browser.Events.onMouseMove` /
  `onMouseUp` subscribing is in `Main.elm`'s `subscriptions`.
- **Inline MouseMove / MouseUp handlers.** Those live in
  `Main.elm`'s `update` — they're short enough that factoring
  out cost > benefit today.
- **Wing rendering.** `viewWingAt` lives in `Main.View`.
- **Drag floater rendering.** `draggedOverlay` lives in
  `Main.View`.

## Dependencies

- `Browser.Dom`, `Browser.Events` — gesture primitives.
- `Html`, `Html.Attributes`, `Html.Events` — view-side
  styling.
- `Json.Decode` — pointDecoder.
- `Game.Card`, `CardStack`, `GestureArbitration`, `Hand`,
  `WingOracle`, `WireAction` — domain.
- `Main.Apply` — applyAction in handleMouseUp.
- `Main.Msg` — Msg constructors.
- `Main.State` — Model, DragState, DragInfo, activeHand,
  boardDomId.
- `Main.Wire` — sendAction in handleMouseUp.
